  "prompt": "Which digital circuit use by data bus to pass data from memory to register?",
  "response": "The digital circuit used by a data bus to pass data from memory to a register is typically referred to as a \"multiplexer\" (MUX) or \"tri-state buffer.\"\n\n1. **Multiplexer (MUX)**: It selects one of many input lines to pass through to the output, based on control signals. In the context of passing data from memory to a register, a multiplexer might be used to choose between different memory locations before transferring the data to the register.\n\n2. **Tri-state Buffer**: This is more commonly used in data buses. A tri-state buffer can be in one of three states: transmitting, receiving, or high-impedance. When multiple devices share the same bus, tri-state buffers ensure that only one device communicates on the bus at a time, preventing bus contention.\n\nThese components ensure that data is accurately and efficiently transferred from memory to registers within a computer system. Additionally, control signals and timing circuits manage the operation to ensure data integrity and synchronization between different parts of the system.",
